# Testing Rules

These four rules apply to every testing operation regardless of
deadline pressure. They are non-negotiable.

## 1. Absolute Data Isolation

- Every test must run against fresh, isolated data — never shared
  database state between tests or test suites
- Tests must clean up after themselves via transaction rollback,
  database snapshots, or container teardown
- Test execution order must never affect test outcomes — any test
  must pass when run in isolation
- Shared fixtures that accumulate state across tests are prohibited
- Production databases must never be used for testing under
  any circumstances

## 2. No Static Pauses

- Hardcoded sleep/wait calls (Thread.sleep, setTimeout with fixed
  duration, cy.wait(5000)) are strictly prohibited in all test code
- All timing dependencies must use dynamic waiting mechanisms:
  - Playwright: page.waitForSelector, page.waitForResponse,
    expect(locator).toBeVisible()
  - Vitest: vi.waitFor(), vi.waitUntil()
  - Network: intercept and await specific requests, not fixed delays
- If a test cannot be written without a fixed sleep, the application
  code must be refactored to expose a testable state signal

## 3. Quarantine Don't Ignore

- A test identified as flaky must be quarantined immediately using
  it.skip or a dedicated quarantine wrapper — never left in the
  active suite where it blocks CI
- Quarantined tests must be tracked in a dedicated issue with:
  - Root cause hypothesis
  - Assigned owner
  - Remediation deadline (maximum 2 weeks)
- A test quarantined for more than 2 weeks without remediation
  is deleted and rewritten from scratch
- Blind reruns (retry: 3 in CI config) without root cause analysis
  are prohibited — they mask systemic failures

## 4. Strict Pipeline Speed Limits

- The critical feedback path (unit + integration tests) must
  complete within 5 minutes
- The full pipeline (including E2E) must complete within 10 minutes
- Suites exceeding these limits must be parallelized across runners
  using matrix strategies or test sharding
- E2E tests must be restricted to the 10-15 most critical user
  journeys — comprehensive UI coverage belongs in component tests
- Mutation tests run on a nightly schedule, not on every PR